3. Optimize a slow JOIN query

Before optimization:

SELECT c.name, o.order_id
FROM customers c
JOIN orders o
ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id;

Optimization: Create an index on the join column.

CREATE INDEX idx_orders_customer
ON orders(customer_id);

Then analyze:

EXPLAIN
SELECT c.name, o.order_id
FROM customers c
JOIN orders o
ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id;


4. Explain when an index should not be used
Indexes should generally not be used:

On tables with very few records.
On columns that change frequently (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
On columns having very few unique values (e.g., Gender: Male/Female).
When the table is updated more often than it is searched.
When queries retrieve almost all rows from the table.

These tasks cover Indexing, EXPLAIN, Query Optimization, and Index Usage concepts.
